Time Series Analysis - Dow Jones Industrial

Siyuan Zheng

April 6th, 2017

Data Description

  • The data is the monthly excess return of Dow Jones Industrial Average from January 2005 to February 2017
  • Where monthly excess return is defined as \(\frac{Close\:price\:of\:the\:month\:\:Open\:price\:of\:the\:month}{Open\:price\:of\:the\:month}\)
  • Historical data is downloaded from http://finance.yahoo.com

# As required, defined the data of monthly excess return as (Close-Open)/Open
DJI = ts((data$Close-data$Open)/data$Open)
# The plot of the historical data
plot(DJI,main="Data of Dow Jones Industrial", xlab="Time(In Month)",ylab="Monthly Excess Return",type="o")

# Making the TS plot interactive
dygraph(DJI)

Time Series Modelling

# To see whether the data need transformation
lambda <- BoxCox.lambda(DJI)
lambda
## [1] 0.894564
# plot(stl(DJI)), this causes the halt of the program, which says there is no periodic component, thus ignoring the procedure of decomposition(removing trend and seasonal)

Since lambda is very cloes to 1, we do not need to make transformation to the data

# since acf of MA model is cut-off, used to determine the candidate of p
acf(DJI)

# since pacf of AR model is cut-off, used to determine the candidate of q
pacf(DJI)

Fitting data using MA(4) model

# based on the above diagrams, we should choose 4 as p of MA model
ma <- arima(DJI,c(0,0,4),include.mean=FALSE)
ma
##

Analysis of four models

AR Model

\[ X_t = 0.1418 X_{t-1} - 0.1088 X_{t-2} + 0.1420 X_{t-3} + Z_t \]

since the p-value of ljung-box test is greater than 0.05,

We fail to reject the null hypothesis that \(Z_t\) is a white noise.

According to the roots of B, the AR model is not causal.

MA Model

\[ X_t = 0.927 Z_t - 0.0636 Z_{t-1} + 0.1482 Z_{t-2} + 0.1954 Z_{t-3} \]

since the p-value of ljung-box test is greater than 0.05,

We fail to reject the null hypothesis that \(Z_t\) is a white noise,

According to the roots of B , the MA model is not invertible.

ARMA(3,4) Model

\[ X_t + 0.5212 X_{t-1} - 0.8175 X_{t-2} + 0.6073 X_{t-3} = Z_t -0.4087 Z_{t-1} + 0.7856 Z_{t-2} - 0.4072 Z_{t-3} + 0.1194 Z_{t-4}\]

since the p-value of ljung-box is greater than 0.05,

We fail to reject the null hypothesis that \(Z_t\) is a white noise.

According to the roots of B , the ARMA(3,4) model is neither invertible nor causal.

ARMA(2,2) (auto generated) Model

\[ X_t - 0.1731 X_{t-1} - 0.9251 X_{t-2} = Z_t + 0.2567 Z_{t-1} + 0.8499 Z_{t-2} \]

since the p-value of ljung-box test is greater than 0.05,

We fail to reject the null hypothesis that \(Z_t\) is a white noise.

According to the roots of B, the ARMA model is neither invertible nor causal.

Conclusion so far

Since AR(3) model has the greatest AIC within the four model, AR(3) seems to fit the historical data better. ARCH model is not being tried for fitting the data, maybe there are some other better models.
